	<h3>Systems Software</h3>

	<p>

	My MSc research project was my entry to systems level software; I
	ported JikesRVM, a JVM written mostly in Java, to run on top of bare
	hardware, without the support of an operating system. The limited time
	available in the context of an MSc project did not allow me to go all
	the way to run applications on, but  the system could readily run
	"hello world" [1][2]. Later, I contributed patches to the JikesRVM
	project to enable support for Opensolaris [3] and, in the context of
	the Google Summer of Code 2008 program, to compile and run with OpenJDK
	[4]. I have also proposed an architecture to make Java's I/O subsystem
	faster by replacing the OS (notice a pattern?) with a hypervisor and
	thus relieving it of context switches and copies [5]. This is work in
	progress.

	</p>

	<h3>Systems performance evaluation</h3>

	<p>

	My research career started with trying to evaluate the performance of
	web content technologies. In the same vein, I proposed and evaluated a
	set of rules of thumb for tuning the JVM's garbage collector in a
	server environment. <a href="#GKS06">[1]</a> 	
	I have also developed a Perl library that parses
	the output from DTrace to reveal interesting facts about the
	co-operation of the JVM with the operating system.<a href="#GS08">[2]</a>


	</p>

	<h2>Projects</h2>
	    
	Here is a list of research projects I have been actively involved with,
	along with a description of my role in them.
	 
	<dl>

	<dt>SQO-OSS</dt> 

	<dd>The <a href="http://www.sqo-oss.eu">SQO-OSS</a> project was an EC
		funded (FP6-033331) effort to investigate novel ways for the
		assessment of software quality with data from OSS repositories.
		I had written the original project proposal myself and served
		the project as its project manager, being responsible for
		talking with the EU and guiding its development. The project
		developed an extensible high performance engine (Alitheia Core)
		that analyses data from repositories and is extensible through
		plug-ins. I was Alitheia Core's lead designer, development lead
		and top source code committer. Later on, I based my PhD work on
		the Alitheia Core platform. The platform is still under
		development at <a href="http://www.sqo-oss.org">http://www.sqo-oss.org</a>. 
	</dd>

	<dt>PAVET 2008</dt>

	<dd>The PAVET series of projects involved teaching new technologies to
		interested third parties. I gave 5 lectures on development with
		OSS tools to a mixed group of software professionals and
		students.</dd>

	<dt>PENED 2003</dt>

	<dd>The PENED series of projects were Greek state funded joint research
		projects for PhD students. Along with Stephanos Androutsellis
		Theotokis and Kostas Stroggylos, we investigated novel ways for
		doing secure business to business transactions, both at the
		architectural and at the implementation level.</dd>

	<dt>PRAXIS</dt>

	<dd>The PRAXIS project looked into methods for performing automated
		document exchange in business to business and business to state
		scenarios. As a research assistant, I designed document schemas
		and a couple of exchange processes.</dd>
	</dl>

